\n< Receptionist >Well, well, young lady. Thank you very much
for using our services today.

\n< Receptionist >If you're going to take a bath, please
bring your wooden tag.

\n< Henry >Well, well, if it isn't Lady Serena. Please
do enjoy the hot springs today as well.

\n< Serena >......I can't be satisfied without saying a
word!

\n< Serena >Are you the owner of this establishment? I
heard that you can take a bath here.
\n< Receptionist >Oh, welcome... Oh?
\n< Serena >...What's wrong?

\n< Receptionist >Ah, um... hehe, what a stunning haircut...
I mean, what an unfamiliar face you
have.
\n< Serena >It's rare to have customers from outside.

\n< Receptionist >W-well, that's true, but when it comes to top-
tier customers, it's quite...
\n< Serena >...？

\n< Serena >Well, that's fine. This is my first time
using a public bath like this.

\n< Serena >Since I don't understand the rules, I want
you to explain it to me.

\n< Receptionist >Huh? Well, even if I say explanation, there
aren't really any strict rules or
anything...

\n< Serena >Even if there aren't any strict rules, there
must be some small rules, right?

\n< Serena >So, first of all, how many attendants are
there?
\n< Receptionist >Soba...?
\n< Serena >Huh...?

\n< Receptionist >Um... Would you like me to explain how to
enter the bath?

\n< Receptionist >In that case, please proceed to the
changing room.
\n< Serena >Hmm.

\n< Receptionist >So, you take off your clothes, put them in
a basket, close the door, and oh, don't
forget this wooden tag that serves as a
key.
\n< Serena >Understood.

\n< Receptionist >And then, you take a towel and proceed to
the bath, and well... that's how it
usually goes.
\n< Serena >Huh... Alone?
\n< Receptionist >Well, usually it's done alone.
\n< Serena >Umm, naked...?
\n< Receptionist >Usually, it's done naked.
\n< Serena >Th-That... seems too impossible...
\n< Receptionist >Are you ready to leave?
\n< Serena >Are there any other baths in this town...

\n< Receptionist >Other than that, some curious people might do
a quick dip in the river...
\n< Serena >Isn't that even more impossible...

\n< Serena >Hmm... But I can't just not take a bath during
my stay here...
\n< Serena >No, I can't even endure this day.

\n< Serena >If that's the case... I... have no choice
but to prepare myself...!

\n< Serena >I've only heard rumors... about taking a
bath alone...!

\n< Receptionist >The baths here are mixed gender, so men
also enter.

\n< Serena >M-M-Men also enter?! Th-This is indecent! It's
going to be a big problem!

\n< Receptionist >...Because we received many requests like that, we
have now set a boundary in the middle.

\n< Receptionist >Since it is a simple construction of amateur
work, please try not to lean on it too
much.

\n< Serena >W-Well, if that's the case, then it's fine.
Even if I'm asked, I won't get close.
\n< Receptionist >So, what would you like to do?
\n< Serena >I'm going in... I'm going in!

\n< Serena >Yes, now I am an adventurer. An adventurer.
One who braves the dangers.

\n< Serena >What is this? I will overcome this level of
crisis with flying colors.
\n< Receptionist >Well then.

\n< Receptionist >Then, if you go to the right, it will be the
women's bath.

\n< Receptionist >The bathing fee is included in the
accommodation fee.

\n< Receptionist >Please take the wooden tag from that box over
there and enjoy yourself at your
leisure.
\n< Serena >Yes, thank you, shopkeeper.

\n< Serena >Excuse me for asking so soon, but what is the
changing room...? I can't seem to find
my room in particular.
\n< Receptionist >The customer is standing right there.
\n< Serena >H-Here!?

\n< Serena >It's not even a room, there's not even a
threshold?! Everything is visible...!
\n< Receptionist >Well, everyone does it that way...

\n< Receptionist >Ah, speaking of which, young ladies these
days tend to change clothes while hiding

\n< Serena >...A towel, huh. It's quite small...
\n< Serena >...Is there something a little bit...

I'm sorry, um, thank you.
\n< Receptionist >Oh no, not at all...

\n< Serena >With this, there's no other choice but to
make do somehow. Somehow...
\n< Serena >Because that's the rule...

\n< Receptionist >Oh my... this is...
\n< Serena >......Ugh...uh....

\n< Serena >If I take this off, I'll truly be naked...
The only thing covering me is a single
towel...

\n< Serena >Ugh! Are you really okay with this...?!
T-take it off...?! In a place like
this...?!

\n< Serena >This is a major event in life...! Climbing
the stairs of adulthood...!

\n< Serena >Neither my father nor my mother would ever have
imagined that I would be doing something
like this in a place like this...!
\n< Serena >Ugh...!
\n< Serena >Haa... haa...

\n< Serena >I-I've become naked... Truly... in a place
like this, all alone, outside of the
mansion...

\n< Serena >M-My heart... it's beating so loudly...!
Can't people around me hear it?

\n< Serena >I-I'm far more excited now than when I left
home alone or when I fought against
goblins...

\n< Serena >It feels like I'm doing something really
bad...!

\n< Serena >L-Let's finish this quickly, let's just get it
over with.

\n< Serena >What, it's not a big deal. Don't they say
that commoners do this kind of thing all
the time?
\n< Serena >This is the men's changing room.

\n< Serena >Haa... I need to quickly get to the changing
room... and get some clothes...

\n< Serena >(T-There are male customers here too!?...
Ughhhhhhh!!!!!!)

\n< Receptionist >Oh... Oh my, young lady. What seems to be the
matter?
\n< Serena >Th-the sauna door... I, right now...

\n< Receptionist >Ah, have you used the sauna? How was it? We
recently introduced it and it has been
quite popular...
\n< Serena >N-No, that's not it...

\n< Receptionist >It seems that even the young lady had
quite a lot of fun... Your porcelain-
like white skin is moist and tinged with
a blush, and steam is rising gently,
isn't it?
\n< Serena >Ah, d-don't look!
\n< Serena >Uuuuuu~!
\n< Receptionist >......Hm?
\n< Serena >.......
\n< Serena >.......
\n< Serena >.......
\n< Serena >...The worst day of my life...

\n< Serena >......To be subjected to...to be subjected to
something like this....

\n< Serena >......I won't be satisfied until I say
something!

\n< Receptionist >Well, well, young lady. What brings you here?
Are you out of breath?
\n< Serena >What's going on...!
\n< Serena >Receptionist! I didn't hear that the sauna is co- ed!

\n< Serena >A-Also, there's no doorknob on the women's bath
side...! Thanks to that, I...!

\n< Serena >You must have seen everything too, haven't
you...!

\n< Receptionist >Oh my... what a misfortune. It seems there
was a lack of explanation on our part.

\n< Receptionist >Speaking of the door on the women's bath side of
the sauna, there was no doorknob, so you
couldn't open it and get out, is that
what happened?

\n< Serena >That's what I'm saying! It's a serious
problem! Fix it immediately! I'm sure
there are other complaints besides mine!
\n< Receptionist >Well, um...

\n< Receptionist >The door on the women's bath side is
designed so that you can twist and open
it by inserting a wooden tag.
\n< Receptionist >Well, well, we have it set up like that...
\n< Serena >Huh? Wha... Why would something like that...

\n< Receptionist >Well, if we don't do something like that, the
men might end up going through the sauna
and entering the women's bath, you know.

\n< Receptionist >Around here, it's common sense, so I
accidentally forgot to explain it.

\n< Receptionist >It's common sense, you know? I just, um,
accidentally forgot to mention it...!
Please forgive my oversight... hehe...!

\n< Serena >Ngh... I see... if it's common sense...
then... it's my ignorance as well...
\n< Receptionist >Hehehe... Did you understand, young lady?

\n< Serena >...I have experienced such a great shame
that I am prepared to live or die. I
cannot easily accept it, but...

\n< Serena >I cannot fully accept it, but I cannot
add more shame on top of this... I
will... swallow my pride and accept it.

\n< Serena >Sigh... It seems like I'll be writhing in bed,
remembering what happened today for the
next ten years...

\n< Receptionist >As expected, you are truly a great person,
young lady.

\n< Serena >...I've been curious about that ojou-sama for a
while now, what exactly is she?

\n< Receptionist >Hehehe... Well, it's easy to say that she has a
unique atmosphere as an ojou-sama.
Seeing her dignified demeanor, I
couldn't help myself.

\n< Serena >I see, so that's how it is. However, if
you're going to call me, it's better to
call me Serena. It feels a bit awkward
to be called ojou-sama by an unfamiliar
man.

\n< Henry >Well, well... Serena-sama, I am Henry.
Although I am a commoner without a
prestigious family name, please allow me
to introduce myself once again...

\n< Serena >Hmm... Well then, Lord Henry, regarding what
happened today as an unfortunate
misunderstanding... I will make an
effort to come to terms with it.

\n< Serena >So, this is just a mere opinion as a user,
but I think there should be some kind of
note regarding the specifications of the
doorknob.

\n< Serena >If necessary, I don't mind paying for the
expenses for that.

\n< Henry >Hehehe... I also reflect on my actions. Well,
it's just a matter of writing a quick
note with a pen. It won't cost much
either.

\n< Receptionist >If it's convenient, I will make an
additional note and consider it resolved
for this time. I would be grateful if
you could accept that.

\n< Serena >Yes, that's exactly what allows me to use it
comfortably.
\n< Serena >Well then, excuse me.

\n< Henry >Hehehe... I hope you will continue to favor me in
the future, Serena-sama.
\n< Serena >Small sheets of paper.
\n< Serena >It seems there's not much to see.
\n< Serena >Here's some alcohol.

\n< Serena >A nice drink after a bath. Erika-sama
says it's irresistible.

\n< Serena >I wonder if I'll become like that someday
too? Hmm...
\n< Serena >Huh? There's a hole here.
\n< Serena >What is it...?
\n< Serena >....

\n< Serena >It's dark and hard to see, but I have a bad

\n< Serena >The curtains here, aren't they torn?

\n< Serena >I can't change clothes in this line. It's

\n< Serena >This board is a little bit dented here.
\n< Serena >Isn't it dangerous? I'll mention it later.
